</h3><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-51_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong> Funding and support </strong></h3><p class="sc-cZMNgc hqfPHB pf-53_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">The ACW’s primary role is to allocate funding to various arts initiatives. This includes support for individual artists, community projects, and major cultural institutions. By providing financial resources, the ACW ensures the sustainability and growth of the arts sector in Wales.


























</p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-55_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong>Advocacy and policy development
</strong></h3><p class="sc-cZMNgc hqfPHB pf-57_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">The Arts Council of Wales also plays a critical role in advocating for the arts at local, national, and international levels. This includes influencing policy development to create a favourable environment for the arts to flourish. The ACW works closely with the Welsh Government and other stakeholders to shape policies that support artistic endeavours and cultural preservation.


























</p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-59_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong>Education and community engagement
</strong></h3><p class="sc-cZMNgc hqfPHB pf-61_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">A significant aspect of the ACW's mission is to promote education and community engagement through the arts. By supporting educational programmes and initiatives, the ACW helps integrate the arts into the broader educational curriculum, enriching the learning experience and fostering creativity among young people.




























</p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-63_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong>Compliance and governance
</strong></h3><p class="sc-cZMNgc hqfPHB pf-65_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Ensuring compliance with legislation and regulations is a crucial responsibility of the ACW. This involves setting standards for the ethical and effective use of public funds, promoting best governance practices, and ensuring that funded organisations adhere to relevant laws and regulations.





























</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-egiyK kKHsVi pf-67_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-ilfuhL ejXpQB pf-68_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-69_ pf-heading-1-h3">Best practices for compliance
</h3><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-71_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong> Understanding relevant legislation </strong></h3><p class="sc-cZMNgc hqfPHB pf-73_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Arts organisations must be familiar with key legislation that impact their operations. This includes the Charities Act 2011, which governs the activities of charitable organisations, and the Data Protection Act 2018, which ensures the privacy and security of personal data.



























</p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-75_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong>Implementing robust governance structures
</strong></h3><p class="sc-cZMNgc hqfPHB pf-77_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Effective governance is essential for compliance. Arts organisations should establish clear governance structures, including a board of trustees, to oversee operations and ensure accountability. Regular training on governance and compliance issues is also recommended.



























</p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-79_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong>Financial management and transparency
</strong></h3><p class="sc-cZMNgc hqfPHB pf-81_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Proper financial management practices are critical for compliance. These include maintaining accurate financial records, conducting regular audits, and ensuring transparency in fund use. Organisations should also have clear policies for managing conflicts of interest and safeguarding against fraud.





























